<subSubSection id="D9F5B9E1FF89FF99FF1DF889FE6DBDA5" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="9150EA6AFF89FF99FF1DF889FE6DBDA5" blockId="24.[151,1436,1906,2002]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FF89FF99FF1DF889FECABDFD" bold="true" box="[199,337,1906,1930]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Etymology:</emphasis>
From the Latin adjective 
<emphasis id="A39B3678FF89FF99FDA5F889FC9BBDFD" box="[639,768,1906,1930]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">decapitatus</emphasis>
, meaning without head, by reference to the decollation of upper whorls in all available specimens, no doubt as a result of dissolution by deep-sea bottom water below the aragonitic compensation depth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9F5B9E1FF88FF98FF1DFF63FA88BA80" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="9150EA6AFF88FF98FF1DFF63FA88BA80" blockId="25.[151,1436,151,248]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FF88FF98FF1DFF63FEA6BAC7" bold="true" box="[199,317,152,176]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Remarks:</emphasis>
The 
<specimenCount id="87E921E3FF88FF98FEADFF63FD88BAC7" box="[375,531,152,176]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="generic" typeStatus="paratypes">two paratypes</specimenCount>
are similar in all respects to the 
<typeStatus id="4E5454C8FF88FF98FC58FF6CFC7CBAD8" box="[898,999,151,175]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">holotype</typeStatus>
. 
<taxonomicName id="56EF91E9FF88FF98FC28FF63FB44BAC7" authorityName="Kantor &amp; Puillandre &amp; Rivasseau &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2012" box="[1010,1247,152,176]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="decapitata">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FF88FF98FC28FF63FB44BAC7" box="[1010,1247,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Belomitra decapitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rather distinct in the combination of shape with numerous, well pronounced axial ribs, and the thin and fragile shell. It has some resemblance to 
<taxonomicName id="56EF91E9FF88FF98FE9CFF1BFD95BA8F" authorityName="Kantor &amp; Puillandre &amp; Rivasseau &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2012" box="[326,526,224,248]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="admete">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FF88FF98FE9CFF1BFD95BA8F" box="[326,526,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Belomitra admete</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the differences are discussed in the Remarks section of that species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
